AGI - The United Nations launched a fund to support refugees and internal displaced persons in the face of climate shocks, with the aim of raising $100 million by the end of 2025. In a statement, the United Nations Refugee Agency (UNHCR) explains that its work to build resilience to climate change is already part of its protection and assistance activities for over 114 million people worldwide. "The Fund brings together all UNHCR's climate activities, including refugees' environmental protection activities" established in 2021, said Olga Sarrado spokesman to AFP, adding that the measure has already collected about five million dollars of commitments.
&nbsp;
According to UNHCR, the new fund will finance initiatives aimed at protecting communities more at risk " providing them with the means not only to prepare for the risks associated with climate change, but also to address and overcome them". "The effects of climate change are increasingly devastating, exacerbate conflicts, destroy the means of subsistence and ultimately displace people," said UNHCR leader Filippo Grandi.
< blockquote
&nbsp;
In 2022, more than 70% of refugees and asylum seekers came from countries highly exposed to climate change
</blockquote
&nbsp;
"Many of the countries that have been more generous in welcoming refugees are also the most affected by the effects of climate change," said Grandi. But "the funds allocated to combat the effects of climate change do not benefit displaced or host communities." The Fund aims to promote the inclusion of refugees in national and local climate policies.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
But not only. Contributions also aim to broaden the scope and impact of UNHCR's climate action, allowing the agency and its partners to engage in climate-related projects in countries where it is already responding to forced displacement situations related to important conflicts. The most striking cases are Bangladesh, Chad, Ethiopia, Kenya and Mozambique. In this context, sustainable resources should be available from the environmental point of view in the most affected areas, providing more clean energy, for example, to operate water supply infrastructure. But the schools and health services used by refugees and communities that welcome them will also be strengthened. &nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;

